<DOC><DOCNO> AP901204-0171 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NY-12-04-90 2258EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Salvador-Missiles     12-04 0211</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Salvador-Missiles,0236</SECOND><HEAD>Salvadoran Rebels Down Warplane</HEAD><DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Guerrillas using asurface-to-air missile Tuesday downed a Salvadoran air force AC-47gunship, the military reported - the second aircraft shot downsince a rebel offensive began two weeks ago.   There was no immediate word on the crew.   The Armed Forces Press Office also reported fighting Tuesday inat least five of the country's 14 departments with 18 dead and 24wounded, most of them rebels or soldiers.   Since the rebel drive began, at least 220 people have beenkilled and 500 wounded.   The office said the gunship was hit about 50 miles north of thecapital.   On Nov. 23, a rebel rocket downed an A-37 fighter bomber overeastern El Salvador, the first such incident in 11 years of civilwar.   The military office also reported a rebel artillery attack ongovernment bases in Usulutan, 70 miles east of the capital, butreported no government casualties. It said five rebels died in thefighting there.   The Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, in its dailyradio broadcast, claimed it killed or wounded 23 soldiers andcaptured two.   The rebels say the offensive was launched to push along astalled peace process.   President Alfredo Cristiani has said the offensive couldendanger the peace talks. U.N. officials have said they see noimmediate danger of that.</TEXT></DOC>